Clinical data analysis

Roman Susdorf

November 14, 2018

Introduction

In this session I will analyse a fictional data set describing the severity-state (numerical) of patients suffering from a disease. The patients received 4 different treatments (Placebo, Treatment X, Y and Z), and their severity-state is monitored over a period of 24 months with observations made at the start of treatment (month 0), and then 6, 12 and 24 months later. We have information on the age and gender of participants, as well as the time since they were diagnosed with the disease (in years).

First of all, the data in csv-format are imported from GitHub using the RCurl library:

library(RCurl)
data <-read.csv(text=getURL("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/romsus/epi/master/treatment.csv"), header=T)
head(data)

Data manipulation and descriptive statistical analysis

Some of the variable names are long and tedious to write. So they will be amended for easier handling:

# change variable names for severity observations at intervals month 0, 6, 12 and 24  
colnames(data)[6:9]<-c("m0","m6", "m12", "m24")
# change column name from treatment.arm to treatment
colnames(data)[4]<-"treatment"
table(data$treatment) # it seems that one observation is faulty (NA for treatment):
## 
##               Placebo TreatmentX TreatmentY TreatmentZ 
##          1         66         64         61         16
# change treatment names
levels(data$treatment)<-c("NA","Pl","X","Y","Z")
# remove the row with NA for treatment: 
data<-data[data$treatment!="NA",]

# then readjust treatment levels to get rid of the NA-level:
data$treatment<-factor(data$treatment)
table(data$treatment)
## 
## Pl  X  Y  Z 
## 66 64 61 16

Then it is useful to have a look at the course of disease severity over time for different treatment arms. For easy handling and plotting, the data are transformed into long format using the tidyr package. All entries from the columns for severity (m0, m6, m12 and m24) are then gathered in a single column named severity. The other new column time_lag contains the month when the corresponding severity observation was made, i.e. m0, m6, m12 or m24:

library(tidyr)
data_long <- gather(data, time_lag, severity, m0:m24, factor_key=TRUE)
head(data_long,7)

library(mosaic)

Let’s assume, we wanted to consider each patient’s time from diagnosis (time.since.diagnosis) which is assigned in the data in years. We could for example plot each severity progress trajectory adjusted by the time the patient has been diagnosed.
Note: time from diagnosis is given in years, severity scores are measured over months

We could calculate cumulative disease severity (sum over all available disease severity) for each patient and plot a boxplot for each treatment arm.

First of all, it makes sense to get rid of all incomplete severity observations. I call the new reduced data set d_red.

length(data_long$severity)-length(na.omit(data_long$severity)) # 101 NA's in severity
## [1] 101
d_red<-data_long[!is.na(data_long$severity),] # 727 remaining rows is correct

To conveniently calculate the cumulative severity, a wide format data frame is created and the new variabe cum_sum added:

d_red_wide<-data[complete.cases(data[,c(6:9)]),] # remove NAs
d_red_wide$cum_sum<-apply(d_red_wide[,c(6:9)],1,sum, na.rm=T) # calculate cumulative severity

The results can be plotted using ggplot:

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(d_red_wide, aes(x = treatment, y=cum_sum, fill = treatment)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  theme(legend.position="bottom")




Post-hoc statistical analysis

Now we can assess the contribution of each treatment on severity at each sampling interval (at 0, 6, 12 and 24 months) using ANOVA. Before we start, I want to compute the homogeneity of variance using Levene’s test (car package) across treatments. If the data would show signs of heteroscedasticity, alternative options could be for example Kruskall_Wallis test or Welch ANOVA.
For each time interval time_lag I will run the Levene’s test and store the corresponding p-value in vector lev.p:

lev.p<-data.frame(time=rep(NA,4), p=rep(NA,4))
library(car)
for (i in 1:length(levels(d_red$time_lag))){
lev.p[i,2]<-leveneTest(severity ~ treatment, data=d_red[d_red$time_lag==levels(d_red$time_lag)[i],])$`Pr(>F)`[1]
lev.p[i,1]<-levels(d_red$time_lag)[i]}
options(scipen=999)
lev.p
##   time         p
## 1   m0 0.2458128
## 2   m6 0.7078456
## 3  m12 0.3621956
## 4  m24 0.4937090

The Levene’s test suggests that severity variance between treatments accross time_lag is homogeneous. Thus ANOVA is a reasonable option in this case.



ANOVA

We assess whether treatment has an effect on severity using ANOVA. A potential influence of variables time_lag, gender or age on the effect from treatment (i.e. interaction) will assessed.

First of all, a preliminary analysis is conducted: the effect of treatment at each sampling intervall is assessed using Tukey’s honest significance test. To obtain a data frame in the temporal order m0,m6,m12 and m24, the time_lag level m6 will be renamed to m06. I will only look at the effects within a sampling interval time_lag. Therefore, only a subset of the data frame (tuk) is shown below:

levels(d_red$time_lag)[levels(d_red$time_lag)=="m6"]<-"m06"
tuk<-TukeyHSD(aov(severity ~ time_lag*treatment  + gender, data=d_red))[[4]]
tuk<-tuk[order(rownames(tuk)),][c(1,5,6, 13,14,15,    28,34,35, 44,45,46,    59,67,68, 79,80,81,  94,104,105,118,119,120),]

A plot with 95% confidence intervals of the differences between each treatment provides a nice overview:

# Function to add transparency to base colours:
add.alpha <- function(col, alpha=1){
  if(missing(col))
    stop("Please provide a vector of colours.")
  apply(sapply(col, col2rgb)/255, 2, 
        function(x) 
          rgb(x[1], x[2], x[3], alpha=alpha))}

# Tukey Plot:
par(mfrow=c(1,1),  mgp=c(1,0.2,0), tck=-0.008,omi=c(0.45,0.8,0.08,0.05), mai=c(0,0,0.0,0), cex=1, cex.axis=0.7)
plot(y=c(1:length(rownames(tuk))),x=as.numeric(tuk[,1]),col=1, yaxt="n", ylab="treatment x time", xlab="Severity difference", xlim=c(-20,8))
polygon(x=c(-10000,-10000,50000,50000),y=c(-500,50000,50000,-500),col=add.alpha(1,0.1),border=NA)
abline(v=seq(-100,100, 1), col='white')
abline(h=seq(0, 10000, 1), col='white')
abline(v=0, lwd=3, col='white')
points(y=c(1:length(rownames(tuk))),x=as.numeric(tuk[,1]), pch=16)
for (i in 1:nrow(tuk)){lines(y=rep(i,2), x=as.numeric(tuk[i,c(2,3)]), col=ifelse(as.numeric(tuk[i,c(3)])>0, 1, 2), lwd=ifelse(as.numeric(tuk[i,c(3)])>0, 1, 2))}
axis(2, at=seq(1,nrow(tuk),1), labels=rownames(tuk), las=1)
box(lty=1, col="grey75")

It seems that an effect of treatment X, Y and Z is only evident at the 24 month sampling interval (red lines). Z has the greatest effect reducing severity by mean 11. However, due to the relatively small sample size of treatment-class Z, the 95% confidence interval is relatively wide.




Model fit

However, a formal model selection should be carried out. A linear model will be used.

Imbalance is not defined formally. Often a sample size ratio of 1:10 between classes is considered being imbalanced. Therefore, our data is balanced enough as shown in the replications function:

d_red$gender<-factor(d_red$gender)
replications(severity ~ treatment + time_lag + gender, data=d_red)
## $treatment
## treatment
##  Pl   X   Y   Z

## $time_lag
## time_lag

## 207 182 174 164 
## 
## $gender
## gender
## Female   Male 
##    243    484

Thus, we will compare each candidate model using type I ANOVA:

m1<-lm(severity ~ treatment + time_lag + gender + age  + tsd , data=d_red)
anova(m1, update(m1, .~. -age)) # p>0.8 means we cannot reject the Null-hypothesis that there is no age-effect. I.e. evidence suggests that there is no influence of age on severity in the model.

We will progress with linear model m3 which considers main effects as well as interaction between treatment with time_lag and also gender. The model explains 63.5% variation in the data (adjusted Pearson’s R-squared). In the next step linear model assumptions (normally distributed residuals, homoscedasticity etc) are assessed using plots.

par(mfrow=c(2,2),mgp=c(1.1,0.1,0), tck=-0.008,omi=c(0,0,0,0), mai=c(0.5,0.5,0.4,0.2), cex=0.9, cex.axis=0.9,cex.main=0.9)
plot(m3)

These plots look good. No coarse deviations from Normality or non-constant variance. The model m3 is used to simulate severity given certain patient characteristics.




Simulation

pred_dat<-expand.grid(treatment=c("Pl","X","Y","Z"), time_lag=unique(d_red$time_lag), gender=c("Female","Male"), tsd=seq(1,4,1)) # The data frame containing relevant variables 
pred_mat<-matrix(NA, nrow=nrow(pred_dat), ncol=500) # 500 severity values will be simulated for each row in pred_dat

Now the mean and 95% prediction intervals will be predicted using linear model m3 with variables given in each row of pred_dat. These are stored in xx, and used to sample from the corresponding Normal distribution.

for(i in 1:nrow(pred_mat)){
xx<-predict(m3, newdata=pred_dat[i,], interval="prediction")
pred_mat[i,]<-rnorm(500, mean=xx[1], sd=(xx[1]-xx[2])/1.96)}



Now we will merge both data sets to allocate each of 500 simulated severity values to the according variables. Then the library reshape2 is used to convert the data from wide to long format.

d_sim<-cbind(pred_dat, pred_mat)
library(reshape2)
d_sim_long<-melt(d_sim, id.vars=c("treatment","time_lag","gender", "tsd"), value.name = "severity")



Using our simulated severity values we can plot for example how (according to model m3) for example severity between treatment groups chnages over time in males and females:

ggplot(d_sim_long, aes(x=time_lag, y=severity, fill=treatment)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  facet_grid(cols=vars(gender)) +
  theme(legend.position="bottom")

Or how the time that passed since diagnosis (tsd) is affecting severity in female and male patients:

ggplot(d_sim_long[d_sim_long$time_lag=="m24",], aes(x=as.factor(tsd), y=severity, fill=treatment)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  theme(legend.position="bottom") +
  facet_grid(cols=vars(gender)) +
  labs(x = "tsd (years since diagnosis)")
